column102: I am a resident and my building had and room had quite a few problems that were definitely looked over. My roommates and I were taking cold showers for a week and a half while also putting orders in which never were taken serious. We had two fridges and one microwave plugged into our "common" room and the outlets kept blowing out and all of our stuff would spoil. We grocery shopped a lot so we could eat comfortably in the room and our money was sometimes wasted. We put an order in for our outlets 4 times and each time all they did was plug in an adapter with a light that turned on indicating it was fine but electricity is internal and clearly if this happened more than 5 times in our room that means you should be checking the wiring and inside the outlets.
column118: Some people who work for campus police are rude. I went in to get a parking pass i didn't see anyone in the parking office so i waited and a woman with a rude tone of voice asked me "what do you want". Being polite I said hi sorry i didn't see anyone in the office i am here for a parking pass. She ignored me for a little then said "just go to the window". I've never had a good encounter there.
column126: He told me that he mostly focuses on juniors and seniors and i understand that but i also want an academic advisor who will focus on me as well being a sophomore. column102: As a transfer student in Hospitality Management I was provided the new hospitality academic plan to follow. Thankfully I spoke with an amazing professor who helped me figure everything out but it made be stress about classes and graduating more than I would've otherwise. column109: I have always felt that there are very few activities happening on campus during the weekends. In combination with the limited number of dining options and the academic buildings being closed, I find it difficult to enjoy being on campus during the weekends. column122: There are not enough options for students to use a meal swipe. In previous semesters, students have been able to use a meal swipe for late night dining options or at the Glow Lounge. But for most of this semester, late night dining wasn't an option at all and the Glow Lounge was closed. And now that late night dining has returned, we can't use a meal swipe. 1851 is very expensive and it's often around $9 for a sandwich with no side or drink. There need to be more opportunities for students to use a meal swipe, other than the dining hall. In addition, I wish that 1851 still had the larger salad options they had during previous semesters. I used to eat a salad from the Glow Lounge or 1851 several times a week. The lack of options for dining makes it harder to eat healthy.

column160: I am completely baffled how Lasell is requiring students to return after thanksgiving. column73: The schedule changed and while I think it is important to have it go to places other than the T when we should be limiting our time going into the city anyways, I hated having to walk down to the T so I could get to an appointment I had in the city. (I had to arrive at the T at the half-hour mark which is now when the shuttle goes elsewhere and I could not take the earlier or later shuttle since leaving early would mean taking time off work and leaving late would mean arriving late to my appointment.) It doesn't matter any more for me since I have no other plans to go into the city; it just bothered me that it made my travel that much more difficult (especially since the change was put in place the week of my appointment).
column77: My issue is more with the restrictions of the financial aid process at Lasell than the office itself. My mom didn't file her taxes in the year that we included on my FAFSA (and we stated that she had not filed on the FAFSA). While that was fine with the government, I was told by the Office of Financial Aid that I needed to present her taxes in order to get any kind of reward or have her sign a form stating that she did file taxes but they were just not accepted by the government yet (which she did not yet do) so even though I have the need, I was awarded no financial aid for this year (other than my merit scholarship).
column102: There is a commitment to academic excellence but I do feel more could be done as I know some people who are just trying to get by enough to graduate. The residence halls are comfortable even if mine is a little cold right now. I feel listened to as a student and I know we value academic integrity. We have a great sense of school spirit (probably due to all of our great events). I wasn't this semester able to register for the course types I wanted; I'm not great with online learning since it's more difficult to stay focused and remember assignments than in person, but all but one of my classes this term were online (the other was a flex class meeting once online and once in person each week). Faculty are usually available for office hours, but after class is now a difficulty if they are online (ex. they shut off the call before you can ask to talk to them). I have had positive experiences with individuals different than myself and that I would say is all thanks to the IC3 and the Donahue Institute for DEI on campus. Tuition paid I think is a worthwhile investment, but I don't pay a lot due to my scholarship. The faculty do care about me. I was able to register for all the classes I need without issues. I think everyone on campus knows me in some way so I would say I'm an integral part of the Lasell Community.
column109: There are some activities on campus during the weekends, but there aren't a lot (I've seen a mix of online and in-person ones though). I think part of the issue is the difficulty of hosting virtual events along with the fact that a lot of students seem to currently be going home on the weekends. I just wish there were a few more (even if it involved only spreading out the ones from during the week-I can name at least 2 days this week that have 2-3 programs happening at the exact same time so while I want to go to all of them I'll only get to go to one each day).
column118: I feel like some faculty could better take into account student differences when they teach classes (and also that others should take them into account less). One of the classes I'm in focuses on adolescent development but, when we talked about the chapter on puberty, it was very cis-centric and as a trans guy it made me uncomfortable being asked to talk about what puberty was like for me-the professor didn't require us to talk but even being asked. Knowing I didn't go through the puberty I wanted to go through still wasn't pleasant. I've also seen the opposite happen where some faculty decided that based on a student's identity they should be able to answer specific questions for the class or be assigned certain topics (I've mostly seen this happen to international students-especially those from Saudi Arabia-where they were asked to cover things like immigration or the international political climate while the rest of us got to pick any topic we wanted).

column160: Find ways to crack down on students not following the COVID-19 policies without making other students do it. I know that this is difficult since we don't want to make any group (ex. professors, campus police) seem untrustworthy or forceful but at the same time I see far more people wearing masks incorrectly/not at all than I am comfortable. I feel like right now the burden is on students to tell other students (with this being especially on RAs who are asked to document all instances that they see even when not on duty). It's frustrating since even when I say something (ex. at the library I have to remind students using the study rooms that they still need to wear masks at least once a week), the students seem to only follow it until I'm gone (ex. I've seen people have their masks down and pull them up when an RA walks in). I have also heard of students faking their Co-verified results by showing screenshots of past green days which means that even having that check doesn't ensure safety at events/classes. I just want us to be safe and be able to stay open, but given the increase of COVID cases on campus along with these concerns I feel like it won't be able to happen.  I think also just finding ways to make this all feel more normal, but I have no answers on how to do that. It's weird going straight from the cafeteria to my room to eat since I'm not allowed to eat in any buildings and it's cold outside. It's weird having to be vigilant on if my neighbors in my dorm have people over. It's weird wearing a mask at all times out of my room even when I'm outside completely alone (I know that this is also part of the governor's mandate and is not only a rule of Lasell). I'm willing to do it because I want to stay safe and have Lasell stay open; I just wish this wasn't such a weird year. I still have Lasell traditions I haven't gotten to experience because of the pandemic and I worry that I'll never get to experience them (ex. Last year was going to be my first torch-light, my first spring week, and my first Marathon Monday here, but now this will be my first and last year experiencing them *IF* these can even happen.) I know there's been some work on doing this like still having U-Belong, Bingo, stuff-a-plush, and the winter carnival, but please keep it up. I don't care how many times I need to show my Co-verified or socially distance; I just want to still have the traditions that are part of why I fell in love with Lasell in the first place.

column102: Maybe it is just a COVID thing, but this campus is super boring. It feels like high school but with dorms. There is no sense of school spirit within the students, only those who are apart of the SGA seem to have that spirit. My RA is literally never around, I just found out that there is more than 2 in my dorm building. I feel like just another body at this school. The heating/cooling situation in my dorm building is insane. The heat is on in my dorm, then the AC is on in the hallway. The second-floor showers of Woodland suck. The shower hoses in the 2 hc stalls are constantly falling off when the water turns on. I've been hit multiple times in the head with them. I feel like I am spending private school money for a community college experience, but the only difference is that most community colleges are fun.
column109: I can't go home for the weekends like a majority of students because I moved here from Arkansas. This campus is literally so quiet and boring on the weekends that it makes me just feel depressed. There are basically no activities on the weekends, no one is here besides a few people and the workers. It just doesn't make me happy being here on the weekends.

column160: I understand what happened in my situation was an outlier. With that being said, in order to make Veterans feel better about their status at the school, I am recommending a VA office, instead of a few staff members taking on this responsibility as well as others. A strictly dedicated office maybe not be utilized as well as many hope, but when it comes to submitting our VA benefits and other questions alike, it will give us a place to go instead of calling every number in the book trying to find an answer. I will be more than willing to take lead or advise as need be on this project as I know how important it is to us as members of the military. I hope this is something you take into consideration.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_6) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.1.2 Safari/605.1.15
column109: I feel as though with CO-VID, it is rather difficult to host activities. On the weekends, I generally find other ways to keep myself entertained, but it has been rather difficult to stay motivated to want to stay on campus, as there are so many restrictions that don't always make complete sense.
column122: I am a vegetarian, and I often find it rather difficult to find food that is healthy and free of meat. I wish that there were more options for vegetarians that are decent. I wish that the dining hall would do simple dishes (such as pasta) more often, rather than trying to make super fancy meals that aren't always appealing. I always loved when we the option of pasta and two different sauces. It's such a simple meal but was always available to me especially on nights when most meals consisted of meat.   I also wish that 1851 used meal swipes. I feel as though it is unfair that with late night now being an option, you can no longer use meal swipes, but have to use dining dollars. Where as 1851 is generally the best option for me as a vegetarian, it is where I go for meals during the day, and wish that I could use meal swipes. Where take three was taken away, I feel as though they should have made meal swipes an option at 1851 so we have another meal swipe option.

column160: I feel as though my biggest issue is simply the dining hall. I wish there were more options for people who do not meat. Also, more simple dishes. Some nights are great, but I feel as though this semester out of all semesters, I have been more dissatisfied with the dining hall than usual.   Rules surrounding friends in our room is understandable, but I feel as though if they live in our building, we should be able to have a certain number of people in our rooms. All students on campus are following protocol, so I don't understand why we can't have a max number of people in the rooms, as long as we are all following testing and covid protocols (I.E. green co verified badge.) But overall, I feel as though Lasell is doing a great job at doing their best to prevent the spread of CO-VID. Obviously, you can only do so much, but I feel as though I feel safer on campus because of the steps being taken. :)

column160: I think this has been a difficult year for everyone. I think Lasell did a good job of preparing and carrying out the semester. I do wish Lasell had mimic others school in some areas. The process over the summer of deciding our plan for this year was difficult, other schools allowed students to know what format their classes would be before picking where they wanted to live for the semester. Also, i really believe lasell should have had student come back earlier and leave for good after thanksgiving. I think that planning to have us come back after break has caused anxiety in students because it could change at any moment. But overall i do think lasell has done a great job with keeping us safe and keeping us informed. I am apart of a few clubs and i know we are trying to get everyone involved, on snd off campus snd i think this is very important to make everyones experience better.

column89: This past semester, professors have not been thoughtful of the current issues students have been facing. Both in class and virtual students have been overwhelmed with coursework while going through a global pandemic, a presidential election that has caused a racial divide, and other personal issues which has taken a large toll on our mental health. Being told by some professors that "late work is unacceptable" has forced students to complete assignments based on the due date and not for the learning experience. Overall, I am disappointed and dissatisfied at the way students at Lasell have been treated.
column102: As a student who has lived on campus and moved to a virtual setting, there has been no difference in my involvement in Lasell activities. The university has always limited the events on campus. College students want to have memorable experiences with likeminded people but we do not have the chance to do so on campus. In terms of education, Lasell usually has amazing professors and educators, but the overall experience is lacking.
column118: Professors in my major courses are different from the professors in my minor or elective courses. Professors in my business minor courses did not grade in a timely manner. This is difficult because it is difficult for me to determine if I should drop or withdraw from the course.
column126: I am an Event Management major with a Sports Management advisor. He continuously tells me to ask my professors for help instead of him because he does not know how to advise me. I attempted to change my advisor but I was denied.

column89: Too many professors at Lasell are giving students weekly busywork. It's a waste. I can't believe I've spent thousands of dollars to attend a school with professors that do nothing but baby and bother us. They are overbearing and do not treat us like adults at all. They take attendance like it's kindergarten instead of just doing a quick 10 minute class recording about a lesson (like the good professoros do) and then just have us turn in our assignments when they're due. I don't understand why we're required to show up for weekly classes when we would be so much better off getting a quick lesson and just doing the work we need to do. It's ridiculous. I've gotten more value from my business coach than I've gotten from this school when it comes to tools for my career. Half of the classes I've taken are useless and unrelated to my career. Some of us actually know what we want to do coming out of college and really don't want to waste our time or money in classes that are not going to benefit us. Lasell should seriously stop being so strict with the major requirements because it's getting out of hand at this point. The fact that in Fashion Comm we randomly got required to take a second math class to graduate is absurd. I'm a transfer student and one of the reasons I chose to come to this school is because you guys took my math credits from my previous school. I'm thinking things are going smoothly and that I'm on track to graduate then you guys decide to add another math class to my major for no good reason. How is merchandising math supposed to help a Fashion comm major? Think about it. You guys should spend less time trying to collect our money and more time focusing on what is actually going to set us up for success. I'm not proud to be a student of this school at all and if I could go back in time and choose not to attend this school, I would. Each year being at this school has gotten more and more disappointing and I've had it. This school is the reason I would never force my children to attend college. I could have been fine in my career without attending this school. I've just wasted time and money that I can't get back and it makes me sick to think that I've learned more on my own about my career than this "university" has ever taught me.
column102: Registering for classes at this university has been one of the most stressful experiences in my life. You require me to take classes that are useless, but then don't provide the classes on the course catalog that I actually want to take and that I know personally will benefit me and help my career. This school is a joke. I'm paying you and in return you make it impossible for me to register for the classes I need to graduate and then don't offer the interesting classes that are in the course catalog. Every experience I've had with registering has been a nightmare because you people clearly don't know what you're doing.
column109: I don't associate myself with this school.
column118: Professors do not look at students perspectives at all. They show up, pile on the work, then leave. Out of the 6 courses I've taken this semester only one professor actually answers. WHAT ARE WE PAYING YOU FOR THEN? When we ask for help, all they do is catch an attitude and talk to us like we're stupid. Get new professors and stop doing your students such a disservice. We're not paying you 30k a semester for you to employ incompetent professors.

I have only had this experience with one Professor, my fashion Professor McCormack. my other professors have been great at meeting my needs as an online student and developing a strong communication system, so I am thrilled with all my classes but that one.

column89: before the pandemic, I was very happy with what Lasell was offering me. I formed good relationships with my professors, and instructions were always excellent. I have also grown a lot because of it. since the beginning of online classes, i feel like all this was takin away, and i find it extremely overwhelming to get accustomed to this new way of learning. Most professors are definitely doing there best with understanding whats going on with person lives, but I feel like i don't learn on a personal level anymore. I am also a senior hoping to graduate as soon as possible, and it is a bit upsetting that most internships are online.
column102: As stated before, when I was constantly on campus, I felt the faculty very much cared about me as an individual. from the change to in person, to emails and online meetings, I feel less cared about as an individual and often feel like a burden emailing many questions all the time.

column89: Some teachers are much harsher than others when I get confused with everything being online.  I don't know if anyone cares about the dining hall anymore but the food isn't always the best but I love love love the outdoor seating especially with classes online and having to sit in my room all day.
column102: I always see kids breaking the pledge we took and hear stories of kids being caught breaking the pledge without being reprimanded.  I think it's very unfortunate that some kids are treated differently from others but I guess that's just how it is.  I understand that we all test twice a week but if that's the case then what is true point of having the other rules then?
column109: I wish there were more clubs.  I had an idea a few years ago that a now retired teacher told me about to make a type of thrift shop on campus where kids could rent out different clothes for interviews and going out instead of buying suits and formal clothing for ridiculous prices.  But I never got around to bringing the idea up with the activities board or even another teacher because of covid.  I don't know if anyone will read this but I think it's still a good idea especially with so many people struggling to keep or find jobs during the pandemic.  They don't have to break the bank for formal clothing for an interview.
column118: Most of my teachers are great.  I always love showing up to most of my classes because I learn something new everytime.  For the first time ever in my whole life I'm actually excited to go to class. I'd like to thank Professor McQuilken especially because he helped me realize that I actually do want a job in PR and that I shouldn't doubt the field I picked anymore.
column122: Ok, so, I need to preface this by saying that the dining hall is not terrible.  There are some days where I feel like I could eat there everyday for the rest of my life while there are other times where I had to order out for several days in a row.  I don't know why the food quality isn't consistent but after awhile it gets to the point where I personally don't want to leave my room for fear that I'd waste another meal swipe on nothing again.  The staff is really nice though.  When one of my family members passed away a few weeks ago, they were all very kind and unknowingly made me feel better.  It's a shame I don't like walking over there anymore.

column122: The food here is awful. The only items you can really count on is bread (bagels, toast), fruit, and the salad bar. The drink are great. The other foods are bland, or just are not appetizing. I got food poisoning once when I got the feta cheese in my salad. The past few weeks the options are even less. One of the things I was told when coming to the school was that the food was amazing. It is not. And as for 1851, every meal should be allowed a meal swipe. I quickly run out of dining dollars seeing as 1851 food quality is better. The late night food was removed this semester but that's when you get the best food. Then boomers was opened up at the dining hall but it was only dining dollars or real money. I am a broke student who would love a meal swipe option.  Also they are closed on weekends and close at 4:30 which is awful when it's the weekend and I can't get good food. I also don't think the time for the dining hall closing is good. On a Sunday I went to get dinner it was around 7 (which is a reasonable time to eat dinner) and the dining hall was closed. There are so many times when I try to just get a drink from the dining hall and they are closed and it is the middle of the day. Another time one weekend I went to get lunch around 12:30 and they weren't serving it until 1. I don't think the dining hall doors should lock in the middle of the day. Keep snacks and drinks available during meal changes. I loved the DeWitt food area because you could do a swipe for a drink and 2 snacks. It was perfect.

column102: Lasell has been a good experience, however the housing options during breaks are not good. The school basically kicks us out unless we can afford to pay extra during the break. This brings concern that low-income/homeless students are not taken into consideration during the planning of school breaks.
column118: Lasell College offers no safe alternative for students with no housing outside of Lasell during school breaks. We get a move out date and are told that we cannot enter back until break is over. UNLESS -- the student can afford to pay extra during the break. Which is like $260 PER WEEK. This makes me wonder if the students here at Lasell who face poverty or adversity on the daily are even taken into consideration when planning successful and Safe holiday break plans.

column160: One main suggestion I have for Lasell University regarding ways they can improve students' experience this term is if they offer safe and affordable options for low-income students as well as students who face adversity on the daily. We as students are already going into debt and hoping our financial aid will cover the costs of our college expenses (it rarely does). But on top of that, some students are left without housing options because they are "too poor" to afford housing during holiday breaks. That is not fair. That is inhuman. It's like were is my financial aid or loans going too? If I have to pay extra ($260 PER WEEK) to stay on campus. COVID makes things hard and resources scarce enough. A better holiday break and housing plan that is attentive to adverse circumstances amongst the student body.
